  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Contemplating the Changes Before the Plum Blossoms
  author: Son Sunhyo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Three strokes complete, ten thousand transformations dwell within.
    Bending and rising through that realm—only heaven and earth remain.
    Gazing on, I failed to notice the plum blossoms blooming wild,
    Yet still I grasp the Supreme Ultimate discourse of Lianyong.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'three strokes' refers to the three basic lines of the Yijing (I Ching), which through their combinations generate all change and multiplicity in the cosmos.
  - key: ''
    value: Heaven and earth (건곤/qiankun) represent the primary dyadic principle underlying all phenomena in the Yijing cosmology.
  - key: ''
    value: Lianyong (濂翁) is another name for Zhou Dunyi (周敦頤), the Song dynasty Neo-Confucian philosopher who wrote the influential 'Explanation of the Diagram of the Supreme Ultimate' (太極圖說).
  - key: ''
    value: The poem presents a tension between immediate sensory experience (the plum blossoms) and abstract philosophical contemplation (the cosmological principles of the Yijing and Supreme Ultimate).
